stage of follicular development?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vesicular follicle","Primordial follicle","Primary follicle","Secondary follicle","Atretic follicle"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis description matches a \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary follicle\u003C/strong\u003E. The key identifying features are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESingle layer of cuboidal granulosa cells (transformed from flat cells in the \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimordial follicle\u003C/strong\u003E)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPresence of zona pellucida\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHas not yet developed multiple layers of granulosa cells (which would indicate a \u003Cstrong\u003Esecondary follicle\u003C/strong\u003E)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ENo antral cavity (which would indicate a \u003Cstrong\u003Evesicular follicle\u003C/strong\u003E)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EShows normal development (unlike an \u003Cstrong\u003Eatretic follicle\u003C/strong\u003E which shows signs of degeneration)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe progression of follicular development begins with primordial follicles, which contain flat granulosa cells. These develop into primary follicles with cuboidal granulosa cells, then secondary follicles with multiple granulosa cell layers, and finally vesicular follicles with an antral cavity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Primary follicles develop from primordial follicles and are characterized by a single layer of cuboidal granulosa cells","The progression of ovarian follicle development follows: primordial \u2192 primary \u2192 secondary \u2192 vesicular (antral) follicle"],"references":["Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press","Fortune JE, Yang MY, Muruvi W. The earliest stages of follicular development: follicle formation and activation. Soc Reprod Fertil Suppl. 2010;67:203-16. doi: 10.7313/upo9781907284991.018. PMID: 21755674; PMCID: PMC5316466.","Zhang T, He M, Zhang J, Tong Y, Chen T, Wang C, Pan W, Xiao Z. Mechanisms of primordial follicle activation and new pregnancy opportunity for premature ovarian failure patients. Front Physiol. 2023 Feb 28;14:1113684. doi: 10.3389/fphys.2023.1113684. PMID: 36926197; PMCID: PMC10011087.","Williams CJ, Erickson GF. Morphology and Physiology of the Ovary. [Updated 2012 Jan 30]. In: Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Blackman MR, et al., editors. Endotext [Internet]. South Dartmouth (MA): MDText.com, Inc.; 2000-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK278951/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47763"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15714"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47763"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-17T17:00:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-17T17:01:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8405"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62316"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji"